<div id="review_2625881530" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2625881530" />
    <a title="Jane" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2194897-jane"><img alt="Jane" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1637732786p2/2194897.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2625881530?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jane" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jane" href="/user/show/2194897-jane">Jane</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2625881530" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7152221111748907252">As its back cover states, this book is a work of fiction, but it&apos;s based on the actual lives of people who lived through the devastating famine and black fever that ravaged the west coast of Ireland in the 1880s. The story revolves around a young Luke Ryan and his family who manage to live through the hunger, Workhouses, fever, land evictions and sorrows of the time. Truly, this is one of the saddest books I&apos;ve read in a very long time and several times I had to put the book aside just to remove</span>
  <span id="freeText7152221111748907252" style="display:none">As its back cover states, this book is a work of fiction, but it's based on the actual lives of people who lived through the devastating famine and black fever that ravaged the west coast of Ireland in the 1880s. The story revolves around a young Luke Ryan and his family who manage to live through the hunger, Workhouses, fever, land evictions and sorrows of the time. Truly, this is one of the saddest books I've read in a very long time and several times I had to put the book aside just to remove myself from the horror of what I was reading. My sorrow is compounded by the fact that this is the area of Ireland where my father's paternal family lived, until they were fortunate enough to emigrate to the US. <br />Author Charles Egan is a skillful writer who captures the history of famine in the 1880s and the human frailty that defines the devastation. You will not be able to read this book without thinking of the many people throughout the world, including Central America and Mexico, who continue to seek a better life because of the desolation they face in their homeland.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7152221111748907252" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


