<div id="review_3591852232" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3591852232" />
    <a title="Terry" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1125722-terry"><img alt="Terry" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1219323696p2/1125722.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3591852232?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Terry" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Terry" href="/user/show/1125722-terry">Terry</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/45785754-the-killing-snows">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3591852232" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2921831164624688233">The Killing Snows might not be a classic but is a highly interesting historical novel. It follows a family through the Great Irish Famine of the 1740&apos;s. Within the story itself, the book contains many interesting historical facts and information. The story itself might become a bit Jeffery Archer(ish) at times. You know what I mean, the prodigal son, the beautiful bride etc.. etc.. It does enough though, more than enough, to hold the reader. I did enjoy it to move on to a second book following t</span>
  <span id="freeText2921831164624688233" style="display:none">The Killing Snows might not be a classic but is a highly interesting historical novel. It follows a family through the Great Irish Famine of the 1740's. Within the story itself, the book contains many interesting historical facts and information. The story itself might become a bit Jeffery Archer(ish) at times. You know what I mean, the prodigal son, the beautiful bride etc.. etc.. It does enough though, more than enough, to hold the reader. I did enjoy it to move on to a second book following the Irish diaspora (mainly to the US) and the effects it had on the families left behind. The Killing Snows explains in great detail the hardships the normal people of Western Ireland had to endure due to the famine. These families relied on the potato as its main food source all year round. When the potato blight struck it left them with nothing except mostly imported corn. Worse though, was the Black Fever (typhoid) that killed many more than the famine itself. An excellent read that I would highly recommend. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2921831164624688233" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


